Today, as we mark the 110th anniversary of the Armenian Genocide, we honor the memory of more than 1.5 million Armenians and over 750,000 Assyrians, Greeks, Maronites and other Christian minorities who perished at the hands of the Ottoman Empire.

This solemn anniversary is also a grim reminder that the same forces of hate and destruction continue to threaten the Armenian people today. In 2020, Azerbaijan waged a campaign of violence and terror against Armenians in Artsakh. Thousands were driven from their homes, prisoners were tortured, civilians executed, and centuries-old churches destroyed. A brutal 10-month blockade led to starvation and suffering before the region was emptied of its Armenian population. This was not merely war ‚Äì it was the deliberate erasure of a people from their homeland.

"Never again" cannot be a hollow phrase repeated each year while history repeats itself before our eyes. We must rise with fierce conviction against the evils of these atrocities, reject hate in all its forms, and hold the perpetrators of these crimes to account.

Name: Schiff, Adam B.
text:
On today‚Äôs solemn anniversary, I join Armenians in California, all around the United States and around the world in remembering the 1.5 million men, women, and children who were systematically targeted in a campaign of mass murder, rape, and brutalization by the Ottoman Empire.

We must never forget the concerted efforts that saw Armenians from all walks of life rounded up, tortured, burned alive, and marched until death from exhaustion and starvation. Entire families wiped out as a result of what the U.S. Ambassador at the time called a 'campaign of race extermination.‚Äô The first genocide of the 20th century.

Today‚Äôs anniversary also reminds us that the United States for too long stood in dishonorable silence on these events. While the Congress and the White House have finally taken that step to recognize the Armenian Genocide, there is more work to do in order to fully support our Armenian neighbors and friends. We must never retreat from that important progress.

I have sat down with survivors and have watched them relive the pain of this history over and over. We cannot pledge ‚Äònever again‚Äô if we do not also acknowledge that, even a century later, the wounds of this tragedy are still open. And in tragic ways, they begin anew.

Turkey continues to engage in a long and dangerous campaign to deny the genocide and silence anyone who speaks the truth. Azerbaijan has also echoed the genocidal language and actions of a century ago, and with the support of Turkey, attacked Artsakh in 2020 and blockaded it for nearly ten months starting in December 2022. In 2023, the Aliyev regime took full advantage of a people they had systematically starved and ethnically cleansed Artsakh‚Äôs indigenous Armenian population.

We must hold Azerbaijan and those who continue to threaten Armenia and its people accountable. Only after the genocide is universally acknowledged and the continued threats to the Armenian community are ended can we truly say they we have honored the memory of those who were lost one hundred and ten years ago and stood with those who still carry those memories today.

The United States must call for Azerbaijan‚Äôs release of Armenian hostages, advocate for the protected return of Armenians to Artsakh, and call attention to the destruction and desecration of Armenian religious and cultural sites by Azerbaijan in its effort to erase Armenian culture and history. The United States must also urge the immediate withdrawal of Azerbaijani forces from Armenian territory, release of prisoners of war, support Armenia‚Äôs sovereignty, maintain international monitoring on Armenia‚Äôs borders, and provide security assistance to Armenia.

Despite the trials the Armenian people have faced and continue to face, it has not broken their faith, determination, or their will to survive. Time and time again, the Armenian people have overcome enormous hardship and loss, and yet, still remain strong and unbowed.

From shoulder to shoulder in our community to the U.S. Senate, I will always stand with the Armenian community.

Name: Patronis, Jimmy
text:
***PRESS RELEASE***

Congressman Patronis Appointed to House Committee on Small Business
¬†
WASHINGTON, D.C. ‚Äì Today, Congressman Jimmy Patronis announced his appointment to the United States House of Representatives Committee on Small Business. In addition to the Committee on Small Business, Congressman Patronis is expected to serve on the Subcommittee on Rural Development, Energy, and Supply Chains; the Subcommittee on Innovation, Entrepreneurship, and Workforce Development; and the Subcommittee on Oversight, Investigations, and Regulations.
¬†
Congressman Jimmy Patronis said, ‚ÄúI‚Äôm honored to be appointed to the House Committee on Small Business and look forward to being a strong voice for hardworking Floridians and small businesses that form the backbone of America‚Äôs economy. More than 33 million small businesses in the United States account for more than 43% of the nation‚Äôs total GDP. Florida is home to more than three million small businesses, which make up more than 99% of all businesses in the state. My thanks to @SpeakerJohnson, Majority Leader @SteveScalise, Majority Whip @tomemmer, and Small Business Committee Chairman @RepRWilliams for the opportunity to help craft and support policies that will foster fiscal responsibility, cut red tape, and grow an economy that works for everyone. As a former small business owner and working my entire life in the restaurant business, I know how hard it is for small business owners to earn a living and make payroll. I‚Äôm excited to work with my colleagues on the Committee to protect our small businesses, provide better opportunities to live the American dream, and help President Trump Make America Wealthy Again.‚Äù
¬†
House Committee on Small Business Chairman Roger Williams said, ‚ÄúI want to congratulate Rep. Patronis on his appointment to the House Committee on Small Business for the 119th Congress. His dedication to America‚Äôs small businesses and real-world experience will bring valuable insight to the Committee. I look forward to working together as we tackle the challenges facing Main Street and champion pro-growth solutions over the next two years.‚Äù
¬†
The U.S. House Committee on Small Business was created to craft better protections and government policies for America‚Äôs Small Businesses. The Committee is responsible for evaluating and addressing the challenges faced by small businesses and analyzing how broader business practices and trends affect them. The Committee holds legislative and oversight authority over the Small Business Administration and its initiatives. It also supports and safeguards small businesses by facilitating access to financial assistance and promoting their involvement in federal procurement and government contracting opportunities.
¬†
Congressman Patronis recently announced his appointment to the House Committee on Transportation and Infrastructure. Learn more ‚û°Ô∏è https://t.co/noYJrhK5cR
¬†
###

I strongly oppose the continued overuse of the Bonnet Carr√© Spillway. Each time it‚Äôs opened, it sends a flood of freshwater into the Mississippi Sound, threatening the delicate balance of our ecosystem and causing serious harm to South Mississippi‚Äôs fishing and shrimping industries‚Äîand, ultimately, our economy.

We understand the concerns of our neighbors in New Orleans and throughout Louisiana. Protecting people and property from flooding is critically important‚Äîbut there are other options. Relying on the Bonnet Carr√© year after year is not sustainable, especially for our coastal communities.

Instead of waiting until we‚Äôre in a crisis, we should be using smarter, long-term strategies‚Äîlike gradually opening spillways over time‚Äîto reduce pressure without overwhelming our waters. That kind of planning would go a long way in protecting both lives and livelihoods across the Gulf Coast.

I‚Äôm committed to fighting for solutions that protect all our communities‚Äîwithout putting South Mississippi at risk.

Name: McGovern, James P.
text:
Congressman Jim McGovern, his wife Lisa McGovern, and their son Patrick McGovern released the following statement upon the passing of Congressman McGovern‚Äôs daughter, Molly McGovern:
¬†
Molly radiated pure joy. She lit up every room with her beaming smile‚Äîfull of laughter, endless warmth, and a sharp wit that could disarm you in an instant. She was unbelievably funny, fiercely loyal, and wise beyond her years. Molly had a rare gift: She made everyone feel special, because she genuinely believed everyone was special. She treated people with compassion and kindness‚Äîalways standing up for the underdog, and making fast friends wherever she went. Her love for the Boston Bruins was fierce, but it was no match for the love she gave so freely to her family and friends. If you ever met Molly, you carried a piece of her light with you. She had that kind of effect on people.
¬†
Even as she faced a rare cancer diagnosis, she did so with relentless courage, optimism, and tenacity‚Äîrefusing to let her illness slow her down. She had just finished a semester abroad in Australia. She passed away unexpectedly in Italy while visiting a good friend and his family.
¬†
Molly will always be the soul of our family. We are so proud of her, and so glad that so many people were touched by her incredible life. We love you, Molly. We miss you already.

Congestion Pricing is becoming immensely popular among New Yorkers, delivering on its promises‚Äîless traffic, fewer crashes, and reduced noise pollution, all contributing to safer, quieter streets.

Name: Murray, Patty
text:
As everyone here knows, the folks just across the border in Canada are not just our neighbors‚Äîthey are our friends, and some families even span the border. It‚Äôs not just personal connections that are strong here, but economic connections. Trade with Canada, visitors, and customers are a crucial part of the local economy in Northwest Washington.

Yet, every week Trump seems to find a new way to drive a wedge between us and our Canadian allies, and a new way to drive business away from our communities. He‚Äôs whipping up a fact-free frenzy about drugs at the Canadian border. The fact is: less than 1 percent of fentanyl intercepted at the U.S. border is from Canada. He has created complete chaos and fear for every day travelers crossing our border. People coming here for work, or just for visits, have been detained. His border theatrics are scaring away tourists and scaring off business.

And the pointless, painful trade war is in reality an enormous tax paid by our families.

Trump is pushing away some of our most important trade partners, raising prices for families at the grocery store, and pushing small businesses to the brink‚Äîsome may even shutter. All of this is incredibly harmful to our communities‚Äîit‚Äôs not the way we should treat our neighbors, and it‚Äôs catastrophic for business too.

I‚Äôm glad to be here in Blaine right across from Canada to shine a spotlight on the real damage Trump is doing with his tariffs, his chaos, his attempts to bully one of our closest allies for no reason‚Äîand to listen to this community‚Äôs stories and take them back with me to the other Washington.

Name: Pelosi, Nancy
text:
Molly McGovern was a person of deep faith, beautiful in every way, and enthusiastic about everyone and everything. She brought joy to every conversation, love to everyone she knew, and was truly angelic in her goodness. Molly was close to every member of our family and spoiled us with her affection and her generosity of spirit. We‚Äôre devastated by her loss.

On the day of her passing, I received a text from Molly as she was visiting Assisi in Italy. How appropriate that Molly was there around the time of her passing because she was the personification of the Song of St. Francis of Assisi: ‚ÄúLord, make me a instrument of thy peace. Where there is darkness, may we bring light. Where there is hatred, may we bring love. Where there is despair, may we bring hope.‚Äù

Not only was that her faith, it was her joy. God blessed the McGovern family and everyone who knew them with Molly‚Äôs special grace. May she rest in peace.

text: These are the types of moments I cherish with my job. I had the distinct honor today of presenting John Edward Bishop of Effingham ‚Äì a true American hero who recently celebrated his 100th birthday ‚Äì a Congressional Record that etches his story into the official record of the House for all time. A WWII Navy veteran, John served aboard the tanker YO-21 in the Pacific Fleet, playing a vital role in maintaining fleet readiness during the war. After his service, he was an educator for 10 years, went on to have a successful career in agriculture, taught Sunday School, and was an avid hunter and fisherman. Throughout his life, John has been a steadfast supporter of his family, community, and fellow veterans. I was also able to present him with a letter from President Trump marking his incredible milestone. Happy birthday, John!

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
It was an honor to join community leaders and volunteers to celebrate the restoration of Las Palmas Nature Trail‚Äîa powerful symbol of what we can achieve when we come together for our land, our river, and our future.

The Las Palmas Nature Trail is part of a larger effort to restore the Rio Grande‚Äôs riparian corridor‚Äîone of the most endangered in the country. Thanks to a $2 million federal earmark, we‚Äôve already cleared 1.8 acres of invasive vegetation, including 32 tons of Carrizo Cane and Salt Cedar. In their place, we‚Äôre restoring native habitat, improving trail access, and creating a safer, more welcoming space for the community.
This work is about more than the environment‚Äîit‚Äôs about taking care of the places we share and building a stronger, more connected community.

A heartfelt thank you to Roque Haynes, Project Manager at the Zacate Creek Green District Coalition; Mariana Salinas, ZCGDC President; Tricia Cortez, Executive Director of the Rio Grande International Study Center; and Martin Castro, RGISC‚Äôs Watershed Science Director. And to the dedicated volunteers from El Azteca, ZCGDC, and RGISC‚Äîyour hard work and heart for this community are what make this possible!

Name: Brownley, Julia
text:
I recently visited the Goebel Adult Community Center in Thousand Oaks, a place where seniors come together to enrich their daily lives through a wide range of programs and services. From social activities to health support, Goebel plays a vital role in keeping our seniors active, engaged, and connected to their community.

But right now, these essential programs are under attack. Republicans are pushing reckless budget cuts to Medicaid and Social Security ‚Äî two lifelines millions of seniors rely on for their health, well-being, and security. And as if that wasn‚Äôt enough, the Trump administration is working to dismantle the Administration for Community Living, which helps protect seniors from abuse, ensures they can access the benefits they‚Äôve earned, and supports crucial services like adult day care centers and programs for seniors facing food insecurity.

During my visit, I spoke with seniors whose lives would be directly impacted by these cuts. The center‚Äôs adult day health services are a lifeline for many, and their stories made one thing clear: these programs are absolutely essential to the quality of life for our seniors.

I will continue to fight back against Republicans‚Äô efforts to gut these programs and dismantle the safety net millions of Americans rely on. I will stand with our seniors and their families because they deserve better. I will protect Medicaid, Social Security, and the services that allow our seniors to live with dignity.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
Each week, we share stories of people across our district who rise above the ordinary and inspire us with their courage, compassion, and quiet strength. Today, we honor a woman whose leadership and service have shaped the very foundation of emergency care in Bucks County. Meet this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero: Barbara Stebulis, of Warminster, Paramedic Chief and Executive Director of Upper Bucks Regional EMS, Inc.
 
Barbara began her career as a teacher at Hatboro-Horsham High School. But it was through EMS that she found her life‚Äôs calling‚Äîand for over 40 years, she has answered that call with unwavering devotion. As a Paramedic, educator, mentor, and trailblazer, she has not only saved lives‚Äîshe has built a legacy.
 
She helped establish the Upper Bucks Chiefs Association and, alongside the late John Costello, helped unite the EMS communities of Upper and Lower Bucks, bringing strength through collaboration. Today, under her leadership, UBREMS remains a vital lifeline for nine Bucks County municipalities, responding to emergencies where others can‚Äôt‚Äîon hiking trails, in remote woodlands, and along the water.
 
And Barbara doesn‚Äôt just lead from behind a desk‚Äîshe leads with her hands, heart, and instinct to serve. While visiting a park in Northampton Township with her son Michael, a paramedic, they witnessed a man collapse on a nearby basketball court. Without hesitation, they rushed to his side, performed CPR, and delivered a lifesaving shock with an AED. It was quick, seamless, and second nature‚Äîbecause saving lives is who they are.
 
That instinct to serve is deeply personal for Barbara. After the heartbreaking loss of her son Brett‚Äîa sixth-generation firefighter with dreams of becoming a police officer‚ÄîBarbara and her husband Lenny turned their grief into purpose. In his memory, they became tireless advocates for the Gift of Life Foundation, raising countless funds and awareness for organ and tissue donation. Out of unimaginable loss, they built something powerful: a mission rooted in compassion and a legacy of healing that continues to touch lives.
 
When asked what keeps her going after four decades of service, Barbara answered with quiet grace, ‚ÄúTo hopefully leave things here a little better than we found them.‚Äù
 
She has done just that‚Äîand so much more.
 
As a certified EMT and Co-Chair of the Congressional Fire Services Caucus, I will always fight to ensure heroes like Barbara‚Äîand the extraordinary team at UBREMS‚Äîhave the resources, support, and recognition they deserve. Because when someone in our community is in need, they never hesitate. And neither will I.
 
Barbara Stebulis has served with courage, led with heart, and lifted our community time and again. We are safer, stronger, and better because of her. Thank you, Barbara. We are proud to call you this week‚Äôs Hometown Hero.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.
text:
This morning at the White House Correspondents‚Äô Garden Brunch, I had the honor of recognizing the heroes of D.C. Fire and EMS.

On January 29th, our nation was shaken by the collision of American Airlines Flight 5342 and a U.S. Army Black Hawk helicopter over the Potomac River. Sixty-seven lives were lost. But even in the face of unimaginable tragedy, our first responders did what they always do‚Äîrun towards danger without hesitation. 

Among them, was Firefighter and former Marine Sean Wathen, just weeks into the job. In the freezing darkness, he stood guard over Staff Sgt. Ryan O‚ÄôHara for nearly four hours ‚Äî a quiet act of loyalty, courage, and brotherhood that reminds us who we are at our best.

Their selfless service is the strength of our great nation, and I will always stand with them.

text:
ABORTION PILL FLASHBACK: SENATE FLOOR 2020

First, the mother is given a pill that blocks progesterone ‚Äì a hormone necessary for pregnancy ‚Äì and breaks down the lining of her uterus. Without progesterone, the baby, whose heart is already beating, is starved to death and dies in her mother‚Äôs womb.

Then, 24 to 48 hours later, the mother is given a second pill that empties her uterus by causing severe contractions and bleeding, mimicking an early miscarriage that can last anywhere from a few hours to a few weeks.

Planned Parenthood will try to gloss over the truth, claiming that a hot shower and some ibuprofen are enough for a quick recovery to get the mother back on her feet.

But on average, the miscarriage lasts between 9 to 16 days and can last for as long as 30 days.

Most of the time these abortions are done at home; so the mother is left to suffer alone, without care or supervision from a doctor, and often without any follow-up until 7 to 14 days later ‚Äì if ever.

The result? Women have suffered tragic, gruesome, and horrific experiences from using the abortion pill.

It has caused nearly 4,200 adverse medical events ‚Äì including more than 1,000 hospitalizations, and nearly 600 instances of blood loss requiring transfusions.

Some women have even died. The FDA has reported 24 maternal deaths from the abortion pill since its approval in 2000. And those are just the officially reported ones that we know of that have happened even with the regulations we currently have in place.

Some women need corrective surgery after taking the abortion pill, and others need life-saving procedures.

And somehow, we call this ‚Äúhealthcare.‚Äù

Name: Estes, Ron
text: Today, the EPA announced a nationwide waiver for the sale of E15 gasoline ahead of the summer months. Allowing the sale of E15 year-round and nationwide is a win for Kansas ethanol producers and drivers across the country. This is a great step forward in restoring American energy dominance, and farmers in Kansas are ready to help provide relief for consumers at the pump. This is in line with my support for the Nationwide Consumer and Fuel Retailer Choice Act, which would make E15 available year-round and provide certainty to farmers, drivers and producers. This victory belongs first and foremost to the heroic survivors who shared their stories and the advocates who never gave up.

By requiring social media companies to take down this abusive content quickly, we are sparing victims from repeated trauma and holding predators accountable. This day would not have been possible without the courage and perseverance of Elliston Berry, Francesca Mani, Breeze Liu, and Brandon Guffey, whose powerful voices drove this legislation forward. 

I am especially grateful to my colleagues‚Äîincluding Sen. Amy Klobuchar, Rep. Maria Salazar, Rep. Madeleine Dean, First Lady Melania Trump, and House Leadership‚Äîfor locking arms in this critical mission to protect Americans from online exploitation.

Name: Fitzpatrick, Brian K.

In an age where personal privacy ‚Äî and the safety of our kids ‚Äî can be violated with a click, tonight‚Äôs House passage of the bipartisan TAKE IT DOWN Act marks a critical step forward.

This legislation creates long-overdue federal safeguards against non-consensual intimate imagery and the growing threat of AI-generated deepfakes. It establishes a clear legal standard: victims, especially children, have the right to have these exploitative images removed ‚Äî and perpetrators will be held accountable.

This is a commonsense, essential measure to protect our families, empower survivors, and bring our laws in line with the realities of the digital era.

In the first 100 days of President Trump‚Äôs second term our nation has experienced unprecedented achievements in a new era of American politics defined by competent leadership, common sense policies, and a commitment to America first.

Among other notable achievements, the President has decreased illegal border crossings to the lowest amount in recorded history, stopped the invasion of our country by para-military drug cartels and violent criminals, deported criminal aliens in record numbers, and restored rule of law in our country.

Under his leadership, we are producing better trade deals for U.S. workers, manufacturers, and ag producers, driving down prices for American families, all while onshoring hundreds of billions of dollars of investments and thousands of good-paying jobs. We are right-sizing the bureaucracy, reining-in reckless spending, and rooting-out waste and fraud, and have already cut $200 billion in unnecessary burdensome regulations.

President Trump ended the woke and weaponized federal government, ensuring the levers of power are no longer used to harass our citizens, radicalize our children, and indoctrinate our troops. We have a Commander in Chief and a Pentagon whose focus is supporting our troops, strengthening our military readiness, and restoring peace through strength.

President Trump is on track to have the most consequential presidency in modern history, and this is just the beginning. The last four years of lawlessness and incompetence have left our nation weaker and more vulnerable than ever before.

As a result of President Trump‚Äôs leadership and sense of urgency, Republicans have never been more motivated, unified, and focused on restoring freedom, security, peace, and prosperity, and ushering in a new Golden Age of America.

Name: Cuellar, Henry
text:
Remembering Bella Blue (Phantom) ‚Äî 2017‚Äì2025

We honor and remember our beloved Bella Blue ‚Äî affectionately known as Phantom ‚Äî whose boundless love, gentle spirit, and playful heart touched every corner of our lives.

From the moment she joined our family in 2017, Bella brought a light and joy that can never be replaced. She was more than a pet; she was a faithful companion, a quiet guardian, and a constant source of comfort through every season of life. Whether bounding through the yard or greeting us with that unmistakable sparkle in her blue eyes, Bella showed us the meaning of unconditional love every single day.

It is impossible to sum up all that Bella meant to us. She was there through laughter and tears, through new beginnings and bittersweet goodbyes. Her presence made every ordinary moment something extraordinary. Bella‚Äôs spirit was kind, patient, and wise beyond words ‚Äî always reminding us to find joy in the little things.

Though our hearts are heavy with grief, they are also full of gratitude. We are grateful for the countless memories, the wagging tail, the warm snuggles, and the quiet companionship she so freely gave. Bella Blue‚Äôs spirit will forever be a part of our family, living on in every smile she brought to our faces and every soft moment we now hold close.

Run free, sweet Bella. You will always be our good girl, our Phantom, and our irreplaceable friend.

Until we meet again.
